<PageLayout
  title="γ-MSH (gamma-melanocyte-stimulating hormone): the MC3R-selective melanocortin"
  kicker="Endogenous ligand"
  description="γ-MSH is the melanocortin that breaks the broad-spectrum mould. Relatively selective for MC3R, it is best known not for pigment or appetite but for a different job entirely — sodium balance and blood pressure."
  updated="2026"
  about={[
    { name: 'Gamma-melanocyte-stimulating hormone', type: 'MedicalEntity', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanocyte-stimulating_hormone'] },
    { name: 'Melanocortin 3 receptor', type: 'MedicalEntity', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanocortin_3_receptor'] },
  ]}
>
  <KeyTakeaways
    items={[
      'γ-MSH is a POMC-derived melanocortin that stands apart for being relatively selective — it is the melanocortin best able to engage MC3R at physiological concentrations.',
      'Unlike α-MSH, it is only a weak agonist at MC1R, MC4R, and MC5R, so it drives little pigment or satiety signalling on its own.',
      'Its signature role is in sodium balance and blood pressure, largely through MC3R — a very different job from the rest of the family.',
      'It has natriuretic effects (promoting sodium excretion) and can raise blood pressure centrally by stimulating sympathetic outflow.',
      'γ-MSH is the clearest example that "melanocortin" describes a family of related signals with genuinely different physiological jobs.',
    ]}
  />

  <p>
    γ-MSH — gamma-melanocyte-stimulating hormone — is the melanocortin that refuses to
    fit the pattern. Most peptides in this family, led by <a href="/alpha-msh">α-MSH</a>,
    are broad-spectrum signals that touch several receptors and headline in pigment and
    appetite. γ-MSH is comparatively picky about its receptor, and its main claim to
    fame is somewhere else entirely: the control of sodium and blood pressure.<Cite n={2} />
  </p>

  <h2>The selective one</h2>
  <p>
    Where α-MSH activates four of the five receptors strongly, γ-MSH is relatively
    <a href="/receptors/mc3r">MC3R</a>-preferring — it is the natural melanocortin best
    able to engage MC3R at physiological concentrations, with only weaker activity at
    MC1R, MC4R, and MC5R.<Cite n={3} /> That selectivity is exactly why MC3R and γ-MSH tend
    to be discussed as a pair: the receptor's quieter, harder-to-pin-down physiology and
    its most selective ligand belong to the same story.
  </p>

  <h2>A job in salt and blood pressure</h2>
  <p>
    γ-MSH's distinctive role is in <strong>sodium balance</strong>. It is a natriuretic
    signal — it promotes the excretion of sodium — and appears to participate in the
    physiological regulation of the body's salt handling, an effect linked to MC3R
    expressed in the kidney.<Cite n={1} /> At the same time, acting through central nervous
    system pathways, γ-MSH can <strong>raise blood pressure</strong> by stimulating
    sympathetic outflow.<Cite n={2} /> The result is a melanocortin whose physiology reads
    like cardiovascular and renal biology rather than skin or appetite.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is why the melanocortin system turns up in discussions of hypertension and
    salt-sensitivity that seem, at first glance, to have nothing to do with pigment or
    weight. γ-MSH is the thread connecting them.<Cite n={2} />
  </p>

  <h2>The honest bottom line</h2>
  <p>
    γ-MSH is the family's specialist in the way ACTH is: it took the melanocortin
    chassis and pointed it at a different problem. It is a useful correction to the idea
    that these peptides are interchangeable — the receptor a melanocortin prefers, and
    the tissue it acts in, can change its job entirely. For the receptor at the centre of
    γ-MSH's biology, see <a href="/receptors/mc3r">MC3R — energy partitioning</a>.
  </p>

